Northern Ireland Minister Peter Hain praised the potential of the IRA statement to bring positive change.
Prime Minister Tony Blair and Irish counterpart Bertie Ahern planned to meet in London.
The IRA's criminal activities, including a bank raid and murder, have raised concerns.
Talks were scheduled with Ian Paisley of the Democratic Unionist Party.
Ahern clarified discussions with Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams.
Both Blair and Ahern emphasized the need for IRA cooperation for peace.
The IRA's commitment to end violence and criminality is crucial for lasting progress in Northern Ireland.
